rt signed by the new CA, and restart again. But this is getting complex, so I should consider if there's a simpler alternative.\n\nThe real problem is that nodes with new certs don't trust the old CA while nodes with old certs don't trust the new CA—we're in a split state. The fastest solution is to update the secret with a combined CA bundle and the new leaf cert, then do a full restart of all nodes at once, accepting a brief cluster disruption to get out of this mixed state cleanly. The remaining data nodes are still running old certs, so we've got a split-brain situation where es-1 and es-2 can only communicate with each other while es-0 and the data nodes form their own isolated cluster. I'm wondering if es-0's \"Ready\" status is misleading—it might just be passing HTTP health checks on port 9200 while being unable to connect to the newer nodes at the transport layer.\n\nMy approach is to create a combined CA certificate bundle that includes both the old and new CAs, update the secret with this combined bundle alongside the new leaf certificate and key, then restart all the nodes systematically. This way, nodes with the combined CA will trust both old and new certificates, allowing them to communicate across the certificate boundary and eventually converge on the new CA once all nodes are updated. es-data-0 and es-data-1 still have the old certs signed by the old CA, so es-1 rejects them. But es-1 is also rejecting es-2, which shouldn't happen if both have new certs—unless the Kubernetes secret update didn't propagate to es-2's pod before it started up. Looking at the timeline, the script deleted es-2 and waited, but it timed out at 120 seconds before es-2 fully came up with the new secret, then moved on to delete es-1.\n\nI need to stop the background task, check if es-0 was actually deleted, and then update the secret to include both the old and new CAs along with the new leaf cert before restarting all the non-ready pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null